  "text": "The S0s with polar rings [CITATION_1] ) are galaxies whose peculiarities have been originated by the accretion of matter from outside. They show a luminous ring, composed of gas, dust and stars, encircling the stellar body in polar orbits. The ring may exhibit a knotty appearance and blue colors (e.g. NGC 4650A) or a smooth aspect and red colors (e.g. UGC 7576). The latest and widest compilation of cases of polar ring galaxies has been made by Whitmore et al. (1990) . In this catalogue (here and after Send offprint requests to: D.Bettoni ⋆ based on data obtained using the Guide Stars Selection System Astrometric Support Program developed at the Space Telescope Science Institute called PRC) they discuss the origin of such structures, estimating that about the 5% of all S0 galaxies has had a polar ring in the past, or has one now. The external origin of the ring is explained by the fact that there is no natural way for internal gas to set into a polar orbit and that the large quantities of HI detected (10 8 ÷ 10 10 M ⊙ ) are very unusual for early-type galaxies.",
